Note:
GraphQL Lexer

Tokenizes GraphQL queries and schema definitions into tokens for parsing.

Supports:
- Keywords (query, mutation, subscription, type, schema, etc.)
- Identifiers (names)
- String literals (single and multi-line)
- Numeric literals (Int and Float)
- Punctuation ({ } [ ] ( ) : = @ $ ! | bitwise and ...)
- Comments (# single line)
- Directives (@deprecated, @skip, @include)

Token Types:
- Keywords: query, mutation, subscription, fragment, type, interface, union, enum, input, schema, directive, implements, extend
- Operators: { } [ ] ( ) : = @ $ ! | bitwise and ...
- Literals: STRING, INT, FLOAT, BOOLEAN, NULL
- Special: IDENTIFIER, COMMENT, EOF
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 0
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_INT as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_FLOAT as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_BOOLEAN as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_NULL as Integer is 6

Note: Keywords
Constant TOKEN_QUERY as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_MUTATION as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_SUBSCRIPTION as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_FRAGMENT as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_TYPE as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_INTERFACE as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_UNION as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_ENUM as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_INPUT as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_SCHEMA as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_EXTEND as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_SCALAR as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_ON as Integer is 24
Constant TOKEN_REPEATABLE as Integer is 25

Note: Punctuation
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 30
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 31
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 32
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 33
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 34
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 35
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 36
Constant TOKEN_EQUALS as Integer is 37
Constant TOKEN_AT as Integer is 38
Constant TOKEN_DOLLAR as Integer is 39
Constant TOKEN_EXCLAMATION as Integer is 40
Constant TOKEN_PIPE as Integer is 41
Constant TOKEN_AMPERSAND as Integer is 42
Constant TOKEN_SPREAD as Integer is 43
Constant TOKEN_COMMENT as Integer is 44

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
Lexer State:
- source: Integer (pointer to source string)
- source_length: Integer
- position: Integer (current position in source)
- line: Integer (current line number)
- column: Integer (current column number)
:End Note

@Reasoning:
Byte-oriented cursor over a flat source buffer with line/column tracking. GraphQL's lexical grammar is ASCII-clean (identifiers, keywords, punctuation, string escapes) so byte-level scanning is sufficient and avoids any UTF-8 decoding overhead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Five 8-byte slots, total 40 bytes: source bytes pointer, source byte length, current position, current line (1-based), current column (1-based).
@End Implementation

Type called "Lexer":
    source as Integer
    source_length as Integer
    position as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Structure
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
Token:
- type: Integer (token type constant)
- text: Integer (pointer to token text)
- length: Integer (length of token text)
- line: Integer (line where token starts)
- column: Integer (column where token starts)
- value: Integer (optional numeric/boolean value)
:End Note

@Reasoning:
A single 48-byte token shape carries every variant. The value slot is reserved for tokens that need a parsed numeric or boolean payload, though current scanners leave it at 0 (the parser re-parses numeric text on demand).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Six 8-byte slots: token_type (TOKEN_* constant 0..44), text pointer into source, byte length, line, column, value (currently always 0 for the scanners in this file).
@End Implementation

Type called "Token":
    token_type as Integer
    text as Integer
    length as Integer
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    value as Integer
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Lexer state is allocated separately from the source buffer so multiple lexers can run over the same source (e.g., for tooling that needs both raw and pre-processed token streams). Line and column start at 1 for human-facing diagnostics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes source_length via string_length. Allocates 40 bytes, initialises slots: 0=source, 8=length, 16=0 (position), 24=1 (line), 32=1 (column). Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new lexer for GraphQL source

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    Let lexer_size be 40  Note: Lexer: 5 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize lexer state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0  Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1  Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column

    Return lexer
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Access
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Returning 0 at end-of-source lets the rest of the lexer treat NUL as a uniform end-of-stream sentinel without dedicated bounds checks at every callsite.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loads position and source_length; if position >= length returns 0, otherwise dereferences source[position].
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Advance must maintain line and column counters for diagnostic accuracy. Newline (10) resets column and bumps line; CR (13) is intentionally treated as a normal character (advanced like any byte) so CRLF files report the LF position rather than two-step CR/LF position changes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current position and column; calls peek_char to fetch the current byte. If the byte is newline, increments line and resets column to 1. Otherwise increments column. Always increments position and returns the byte that was consumed.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Set line to line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: Reset column
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Return char
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Whitespace and Comments
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
GraphQL treats comma as whitespace (per spec section 2.1.2), and supports # line comments alongside standard whitespace. Folding both into a single skip loop is essential because the lexer never emits comma or comment tokens directly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops calling peek_char and dispatching: space (32), tab (9), LF (10), CR (13), comma (44) each advance one char; "#" (35) calls skip_comment which consumes to end-of-line; any other character breaks the loop.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace and comments

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        Note: Check for whitespace
        If char is equal to 32:  Note: Space
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 9:  Note: Tab
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 13:  Note: \r
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 44:  Note: Comma (treated as whitespace in GraphQL)
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 35:  Note: # (comment)
            proc skip_comment from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
GraphQL has only line comments (no block comments), so a single loop consuming bytes until LF or EOF is sufficient. Skipping the "#" before the loop avoids needing the loop to re-skip it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances past the "#", then loops calling peek_char; breaks on EOF (0) or newline (10) without consuming the newline (skip_whitespace will handle the newline on its next iteration).
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip single-line comment (# to end of line)

    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip #

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralised constructor so every scanner produces identically-sized 48-byte tokens. The value parameter is currently 0 for all scanners — it exists so future scanners (e.g., an in-lexer integer parser) can attach payloads without changing the token layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 48 bytes and writes all six fields at their offsets 0/8/16/24/32/40. Returns 0 on allocation failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, text as Integer, length as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create a new token

    Let token_size be 48  Note: Token: 6 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, text
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 40, value

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Identifier and Keyword Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
GraphQL names start with [A-Za-z_], which is the standard NameStart class from the spec. Including underscore in the same predicate avoids a separate check in scan_identifier.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if 65 <= char <= 90 (A-Z) or 97 <= char <= 122 (a-z) or char == 95 (underscore), otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic or underscore

    Note: A-Z
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: a-z
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: _
    If char is equal to 95:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit detection is used by both number scanning and identifier continuation classification. A single range check is faster than table lookup at this granularity.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if 48 <= char <= 57, otherwise 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
GraphQL NameContinue class is [A-Za-z0-9_]. Since is_alpha already includes underscore, composing is_alpha with is_digit covers the full continuation class.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 1 if is_alpha returns 1; otherwise returns the result of is_digit.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric or underscore

    Let alpha be proc is_alpha from char
    If alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let digit be proc is_digit from char
    Return digit
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifiers and keywords share the same lexical shape (NameStart followed by NameContinue*). Scanning once and then post-classifying through check_keyword centralises the keyword table and avoids a separate keyword-aware scanner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position, line, column, then loops advancing while is_alphanumeric holds. Computes length and points text_ptr at source+start_position. Calls check_keyword to refine the token type from TOKEN_IDENTIFIER into a TOKEN_QUERY/MUTATION/etc. constant when the lexeme matches a reserved word.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Note: Scan identifier characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric from char

        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position
    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Note: Check for keywords
    Let token_type be proc check_keyword with text_ptr, length

    Return proc create_token with token_type, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Length-first dispatch (group keywords by their byte length, then compare within the group) cuts the average string-compare count significantly because identifiers and keywords differ in length more often than in content. Within each length group, candidates are tested in order of frequency in real GraphQL documents.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Branches on length (2, 4, 5, 6, 8, 9, 10, 12). For each candidate within a length, allocates the keyword string, calls string_equals_range, then deallocates. Returns the matching TOKEN_* constant on the first match. Falls back to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER when no keyword matches.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Per-call allocation/free of every candidate keyword is expensive; future improvement is to pre-allocate keyword strings once at module init and reuse.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "check_keyword" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if identifier is a keyword

    Note: query (5)
    If length is equal to 5:
        Let expected be proc create_string from StringCore with "query"
        Let match be proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 5
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_QUERY
        End If
    End If

    Note: mutation (8)
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "mutation"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 8
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MUTATION
        End If
    End If

    Note: subscription (12)
    If length is equal to 12:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "subscription"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 12
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SUBSCRIPTION
        End If
    End If

    Note: fragment (8)
    If length is equal to 8:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "fragment"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 8
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FRAGMENT
        End If
    End If

    Note: type (4)
    If length is equal to 4:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "type"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 4
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TYPE
        End If

        Note: enum (4)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "enum"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 4
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ENUM
        End If

        Note: null (4)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "null"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 4
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NULL
        End If

        Note: true (4)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "true"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 4
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BOOLEAN
        End If
    End If

    Note: interface (9)
    If length is equal to 9:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "interface"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 9
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INTERFACE
        End If
    End If

    Note: union (5)
    If length is equal to 5:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "union"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 5
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_UNION
        End If

        Note: input (5)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "input"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 5
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_INPUT
        End If

        Note: false (5)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "false"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 5
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BOOLEAN
        End If
    End If

    Note: schema (6)
    If length is equal to 6:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "schema"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 6
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SCHEMA
        End If

        Note: scalar (6)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "scalar"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 6
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_SCALAR
        End If

        Note: extend (6)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "extend"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 6
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_EXTEND
        End If
    End If

    Note: directive (9)
    If length is equal to 9:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "directive"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 9
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DIRECTIVE
        End If
    End If

    Note: implements (10)
    If length is equal to 10:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "implements"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 10
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IMPLEMENTS
        End If

        Note: repeatable (10)
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "repeatable"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 10
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_REPEATABLE
        End If
    End If

    Note: on (2)
    If length is equal to 2:
        Set expected to proc create_string from StringCore with "on"
        Set match to proc string_equals_range with text, expected, 0, 2
        proc deallocate from Layout with expected
        If match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ON
        End If
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer needs to compare a range of bytes inside the source buffer against a keyword string without slicing. A range-aware compare avoids the cost of allocating a substring for the comparison.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates index 0..length-1 reading str1[start+index] and str2[index]; returns 0 on the first mismatch, 1 if all bytes match.
@End Implementation

Process called "string_equals_range" takes str1 as Integer, str2 as Integer, start as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Compare string range for equality

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than length:
        Let char1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, start plus index
        Let char2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, index

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: String Literal Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
GraphQL supports two string forms: regular " ... " and block """ ... """. Distinguishing them requires three-byte lookahead at entry; after that the scanner can pick the right body scanner. The token text includes the surrounding quotes so the parser can detect block-string mode.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Records start_position with the cursor at the opening quote. Consumes the first ". Peeks for a second " and, if present, consumes it and peeks for a third "; three quotes set is_multiline=1. Dispatches to scan_multiline_string_content or scan_string_content accordingly. Builds a TOKEN_STRING with text spanning the entire literal including delimiters.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal (single or multi-line)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip opening "

    Note: Check for multi-line string (""")
    Let is_multiline be 0
    Let char1 be proc peek_char from lexer

    If char1 is equal to 34:  Note: "
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Let char2 be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char2 is equal to 34:  Note: "
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set is_multiline to 1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Scan string content
    If is_multiline is equal to 1:
        proc scan_multiline_string_content from lexer
    Otherwise:
        proc scan_string_content from lexer
    End If

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position
    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Return proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-line GraphQL strings end at the next unescaped quote. Escape sequences are not decoded here; the scanner simply skips the byte after a backslash so escaped quotes do not falsely terminate the string. Escape decoding is the parser/consumer's responsibility.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops: on EOF (0) break, on " (34) consume the closing quote and break, on backslash (92) consume two characters (the backslash and the escaped byte). Any other byte advances one position.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_string_content" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan single-line string content

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash (escape)
            proc advance_char from lexer
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip escaped char
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Block strings terminate at the first """ sequence. The scanner needs three bytes of lookahead at every potential terminator. Embedded single quotes in block strings are intentionally not treated as escape candidates — the only way to embed """ is the spec's backslash-prefix sequence which the parser handles.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops scanning bytes; on EOF break. On ", consumes it then peeks for a second ", and if found, consumes that and peeks for a third "; if all three match, consumes the third and breaks. Otherwise the """ check has consumed one or two extra quotes which become part of the string body — acceptable because the body is preserved verbatim including delimiters.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_multiline_string_content" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan multi-line string content (""")

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

        If char is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 34:  Note: Check for """
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let char1 be proc peek_char from lexer

            If char1 is equal to 34:
                proc advance_char from lexer
                Let char2 be proc peek_char from lexer

                If char2 is equal to 34:
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                    Break
                End If
                End If
            Otherwise:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Numeric Literal Scanning
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
GraphQL numbers may be Int or Float, with optional sign and optional exponent. A single scanner tracks an is_float flag that flips on encountering "." or "e", then chooses TOKEN_INT vs TOKEN_FLOAT at the end. Doing it in one pass avoids backtracking after a decimal point is seen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1) Optionally consumes "-". 2) Consumes a run of digits. 3) If next byte is ".", marks float, consumes "." and the fractional digit run. 4) If next byte is "e", marks float, consumes "e", an optional "+" or "-", and the exponent digits. 5) Emits TOKEN_INT or TOKEN_FLOAT based on is_float, text spanning from start_position to current.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan numeric literal (Int or Float)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32

    Let is_float be 0

    Note: Scan optional negative sign
    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        proc advance_char from lexer
    End If

    Note: Scan digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
        Let is_dig be proc is_digit from char

        If is_dig is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char from lexer

        Note: Scan fractional digits
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
            Set is_dig to proc is_digit from char

            If is_dig is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            proc advance_char from lexer
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent
    Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
    If char is equal to 101:  Note: e
        Set is_float to 1
        proc advance_char from lexer

        Note: Optional sign
        Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 43:  Note: +
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If

        Note: Scan exponent digits
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set char to proc peek_char from lexer
            Set is_dig to proc is_digit from char

            If is_dig is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            proc advance_char from lexer
        End While
    End If

    Let end_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be end_position minus start_position
    Let text_ptr be source plus start_position

    Let token_type be TOKEN_INT
    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to TOKEN_FLOAT
    End If

    Return proc create_token with token_type, text_ptr, length, line, column, 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Single dispatcher classifying the next non-whitespace byte. Order matters: alpha first (identifiers and keywords are most common), then digit/negative (numbers), strings, single-character punctuation, and finally the three-byte spread "...". Unknown characters are silently skipped to prevent the lexer from getting stuck.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls skip_whitespace first. If EOF emits TOKEN_EOF. Else dispatches: is_alpha -> scan_identifier; is_digit or "-" -> scan_number; '"' -> scan_string; otherwise sets text_ptr at source+position and checks every single-byte punctuation literal in a sequence of If blocks (each consuming exactly one char). Special-cases "..." (byte 46 thrice) into TOKEN_SPREAD. Any unrecognised byte is advanced past via recursion into next_token.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from lexer

    proc skip_whitespace from lexer

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: EOF
    If char is equal to 0:
        Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, 0, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    Let is_alpha_char be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha_char is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_identifier from lexer
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    Let is_digit_char be proc is_digit from char
    If is_digit_char is equal to 1:
        Return proc scan_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Negative numbers
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Return proc scan_number from lexer
    End If

    Note: Strings
    If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Return proc scan_string from lexer
    End If

    Note: Single-character tokens
    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let text_ptr be source plus position

    Note: {
    If char is equal to 123:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACE, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: }
    If char is equal to 125:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACE, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: (
    If char is equal to 40:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LPAREN, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: )
    If char is equal to 41:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RPAREN, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: [
    If char is equal to 91:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_LBRACKET, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: ]
    If char is equal to 93:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_RBRACKET, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: :
    If char is equal to 58:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_COLON, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: =
    If char is equal to 61:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EQUALS, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: @
    If char is equal to 64:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AT, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: $
    If char is equal to 36:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_DOLLAR, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: !
    If char is equal to 33:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_EXCLAMATION, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: |
    If char is equal to 124:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_PIPE, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: &
    If char is equal to 38:
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Return proc create_token with TOKEN_AMPERSAND, text_ptr, 1, line, column, 0
    End If

    Note: ... (spread operator)
    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Let char1 be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char1 is equal to 46:
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let char2 be proc peek_char from lexer
            If char2 is equal to 46:
                proc advance_char from lexer
                Return proc create_token with TOKEN_SPREAD, text_ptr, 3, line, column, 0
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Unknown character - skip it
    proc advance_char from lexer
    Return proc next_token from lexer
End Process

Note: End of GraphQL Lexer
